<item>
            <title>[CASSANDRA-12598] BailErrorStragery alike for ANTLR grammar parsing</title>
                <link>https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/CASSANDRA-12598</link>
                <project id="12310865" key="CASSANDRA">Apache Cassandra</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;CQL parsing is missing a mechanism similar to &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.antlr.org/api/Java/org/antlr/v4/runtime/BailErrorStrategy.html&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;http://www.antlr.org/api/Java/org/antlr/v4/runtime/BailErrorStrategy.html&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This solves:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul class=&quot;alternate&quot; type=&quot;square&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Stopping parsing instead of continuing when we&apos;ve got already an error which is wasteful.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Any skipped java code tied to &apos;recovered&apos; missing tokens might later cause java exceptions (think non-init variables, non incremented integers (div by zero), etc.) which will bubble up directly and will hide properly formatted error messages to the user with no indication on what went wrong at all. Just a cryptic NPE i.e&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
</description>
